posts.name: Gavin Matthews
posts.cooked:
ChocolateFreckle:

The = operator is an assignment, not a comparison.  For a comparison, use == , BUT you should never compare two floating point numbers for equality.  What you’re really interested in is whether it’s sufficiently close (the “small range error”), which you could test with:

and then you need to pick an appropriate value for k_tolerance .

If you explain more about what you’re trying to do, we might be able to suggest a better approach.
I get the general gist of your reading, but I’m confused about where to write it. This is our team’s GitHub repository. frc4087/Rummbly.Jr (github.com)

Our team has a CANcoder attached at the end of an arm and want a motor (not the one on the end of the arm but one in our intake) to start once the arm moves to setpoint 1(or in the diagram above, position 1). This method is part of our team’s intake and launching feature on the robot. I’m trying to rewrite our old method and am having trouble changing it to use an external encoder (it was previously written for a SparkMax but we’ve since changed to a Motor with an internal Motor control and an external encoder).

What we have now is called ‘checkSet’ and starts on 173 in FrankenArm. Is there any other information I can provide that would be helpful?

posts.name: Gavin Matthews
posts.cooked:
I’m looking at FrankenArm , and I think this ought to extend SubsystemBase and not TimedRobot .  You should have exactly one instance of Robot in your whole program.

The stuff that you put in teleopPeriodic should end up in the default command for this subsystem.

More later …

posts.name: Chadfrom7226
posts.cooked: Also look into remote or synced CANcoder
What do you mean by this?

posts.name: Chadfrom7226
posts.cooked:
The TalonFX supports various remote sensors. Remote sensors allow onboard closed-loop functionality at rates faster than a traditional robot processor (~1Khz) by reading the remote sensor directly ...

If you’re using a CTRE motor (Kraken/Falcon), you can set the system up to do position control based on a CANCoder
